msgid ""
"In the above example, the `/file` command is used to insert the contents of "
"the `Cargo.toml` file (or all `Cargo.toml` files present in the project) "
"into the rule."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:196
msgid "Nesting Rules"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:198
msgid ""
"Similar to adding rules to the default rules, you can nest rules within "
"other rules with the `/prompt` command (only supported in Text Threads "
"currently)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:200
msgid "You might want to nest rules to:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:202
msgid "Create templates on the fly"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:203
msgid ""
"Break collections like docs or references into smaller, mix-and-matchable "
"parts"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:204
msgid ""
"Create variants of a similar rule (e.g., `Async Rust - Tokio` vs. `Async "
"Rust - Async-std`)"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:222
msgid ""
"_The text in parentheses above are comments and are not part of the rule._"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:224
msgid ""
"**Note:** While you technically _can_ nest a rule within itself, we wouldn't "
"recommend it (in the strongest of terms.) Use at your own risk!"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:226
msgid ""
"By using nested rules, you can create modular and reusable rule components "
"that can be combined in various ways to suit different scenarios."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:228
msgid ""
"**Note:** When using slash commands to bring in additional context, the "
"injected content can be edited directly inline in the text thread—edits here "
"will not propagate to the saved rules."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:230
msgid "Extensibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:232
msgid "Additional slash commands can be provided by extensions."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:234
msgid ""
"See [Extension: Slash Commands](../extensions/slash-commands.md) to learn "
"how to create your own."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:236
msgid "Text Threads vs. Threads"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:238
msgid ""
"For some time, text threads were the only way to interact with AI in Zed. In "
"May 2025, we introduced a new version of the agent panel, which, as opposed "
"to being editor-based, is optimized for readability. Visit [the Agent Panel "
"page](./agent-panel.md) to learn more about it."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:242
msgid ""
"More importantly, aside from the many UI differences, the major aspect that "
"sets one apart from the other is that tool calls don't work in Text Threads. "
"Due to that, it's accurate to say that Text Threads aren't conceptually "
"agentic, as they can't perform any action on your behalf (or any action at "
"all)."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:245
msgid ""
"Think of it more like a regular/\"traditional\" AI chat, where the only "
"thing you can get from the model is simply just text. Consequently, [MCP "
"servers](./mcp.md) and [external agents](./external-agents.md) are also not "
"available in Text Threads."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:248
msgid "Advanced Concepts"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:250
msgid "Rule Templates"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:252
msgid ""
"Zed uses rule templates to power internal assistant features, like the "
"terminal assistant, or the content rules used in the inline assistant."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:254
msgid "Zed has the following internal rule templates:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:256
msgid "`content_prompt.hbs`: Used for generating content in the editor."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:257
msgid ""
"`terminal_assistant_prompt.hbs`: Used for the terminal assistant feature."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:259
msgid ""
"At this point it is unknown if we will expand templates further to be user-"
"creatable."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:261
msgid "Overriding Templates"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:263
msgid ""
"**Note:** It is not recommended to override templates unless you know what "
"you are doing. Editing templates will break your assistant if done "
"incorrectly."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:265
msgid ""
"Zed allows you to override the default rules used for various assistant "
"features by placing custom Handlebars (.hbs) templates in your `~/.config/"
"zed/prompt_overrides` directory."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:267
msgid "The following templates can be overridden:"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:269
msgid ""
"[`content_prompt.hbs`](https://github.com/zed-industries/zed/tree/main/"
"assets/prompts/content_prompt.hbs): Used for generating content in the "
"editor."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:271
msgid ""
"[`terminal_assistant_prompt.hbs`](https://github.com/zed-industries/zed/tree/"
"main/assets/prompts/terminal_assistant_prompt.hbs): Used for the terminal "
"assistant feature."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:273
msgid ""
"**Note:** Be sure you want to override these, as you'll miss out on "
"iteration on our built-in features. This should be primarily used when "
"developing Zed."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:276
msgid ""
"You can customize these templates to better suit your needs while "
"maintaining the core structure and variables used by Zed. Zed will "
"automatically reload your prompt overrides when they change on disk."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:279
msgid ""
"Consult Zed's [assets/prompts](https://github.com/zed-industries/zed/tree/"
"main/assets/prompts) directory for current versions you can play with."
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:281
msgid "History"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:283
msgid ""
"After you submit your first message in a text thread, a name for your "
"context is generated by the language model, and the context is automatically "
"saved to your file system in"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:285
msgid "`~/.config/zed/conversations` (macOS)"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:286
msgid "`~/.local/share/zed/conversations` (Linux)"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:287
msgid "`%LocalAppData%\\Zed\\conversations` (Windows)"
msgstr ""

#: src/ai/text-threads.md:289
msgid ""
"You can access and load previous contexts by clicking on the history button "
"in the top-left corner of the agent panel."
msgstr ""

